# BURST — Bedside UGIB Risk Stratification and Transfusion

A six-feature random-forest model for early identification of high-risk
upper gastrointestinal bleeding (UGIB) and prediction of transfusion need,
using only data available within the first hour of emergency-department
presentation.

Developed for an MSc thesis (Health Statistics & Data Analytics, Aristotle
University of Thessaloniki) on a single-centre retrospective cohort
(n = 133) at the First Department of Internal Medicine, Evangelismos
General Hospital, Athens.

## Disclaimer
Research and academic use only. This is a proof-of-concept model that has
undergone internal validation only and is **not** intended or validated for
clinical decision-making. No patient data are included in this repository.

## Repository contents
- `eosfeatureselect.R` — feature selection (Part 1)
- `ugibpart2.R` — model training, validation, comparators, figures (Part 2)
- `BURSTpipeline.R`

## Requirements
R 4.5.3, with: readxl, dplyr, tidyr, ggplot2, rpart, rpart.plot,
randomForest, glmnet, pROC, patchwork, ggplotify.

## Data availability
The underlying data contain identifying patient information and are not
publicly available (GDPR and ethics-committee restrictions). De-identified
data may be available on reasonable request, subject to approval by the
Evangelismos Scientific Council and Bioethics Committee.

## Ethics
Reviewed and approved by the Evangelismos General Hospital Scientific 
Council and Bioethics Committee (Protocol No. 452, 17 December 2025).

## Reporting
Developed and reported per TRIPOD+AI; risk of bias assessed with PROBAST.

## Author and supervision
Georgios Pournaras, MD, MSc(c) — author; designed and implemented the analysis pipeline.
Andigoni Malousi, PhD, MSc — supervision; School of Medicine, AUTh.

## Citation
Pournaras G. *Combining Machine Learning Predictive Models and Traditional
Scoring Systems for Early Identification of Severe UGIB and a Possible Tool
to Optimize Transfusion Strategies.* MSc thesis, Aristotle University of
Thessaloniki, 2026.

